ach to central locations (downtowns and midtowns) has contributed to strengthening various urban functions, such as urban vitality, pedestrian and bicyclist safety, tourism, and more. However, it has also put pressure on less affluent, peripheral, and fragile areas due to higher levels of consumption and waste generation. Balsas calls attention to the need to base urban revitalization interventions on more spatially and socially just interventions coupled with sustainable consumption practices that do not necessarily entail high growth levels, but instead aim to improve the quality of city life.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aSustainable urban development-Europe. 0aSustainable urban development-United States. 0aUrban renewal-Europe. 0aUrban renewal-United States. 0aWalking-Europe. 0aWalking-United States. 4aCultural Studies : Cultural Studies. 4aEnvironmental Studies : Environmental Politics. 4aEnvironmental Studies : Environmental Studies. 4aPublic Policy : Urban and Regional Planning. 4aSociology : Urban Studies. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / City Planning & Urban Development.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2019z978311149143140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143847629240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438476292423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438476292/original  a978-3-11-149143-1  SUNY Press eBook Package 2019b2019  aGBV-deGruyter-alles